00:17:13,541 --> 00:17:19,366
So that was one of the things I remember Lee saying, it wasn't early, but maybe half a year into it,

261
00:17:19,566 --> 00:17:26,191
where you realize that the combat, the maps, the turn-based takes, it needs quite a bit of space.

262
00:17:26,792 --> 00:17:29,874
Way more than we actually were planning for initially.

263
00:17:29,914 --> 00:17:34,037
So our first couple of maps, once we started putting enough into them, became too cramped.

264
00:17:34,257 --> 00:17:36,459
Yeah, really cramped and claustrophobic feeling.

265
00:17:38,663 --> 00:17:43,585
So we learned what a small map is and what a large map is.

266
00:17:45,906 --> 00:17:50,187
And then we quite early, so it's completely tile-based, right?

267
00:17:50,207 --> 00:17:53,788
So we made sure that everything worked within that system.

268
00:17:54,968 --> 00:17:58,069
And we were actually kind of generating ground

269
00:17:58,129 --> 00:17:59,650
and everything around it for a while.

270
00:17:59,670 --> 00:18:04,831
And, well, we learned that that's, like Lee said,

271
00:18:04,871 --> 00:18:07,772
that we can't create the quality with that type of system.

272
00:18:08,370 --> 00:18:11,932
But if I should say one thing for the developers out there,

273
00:18:12,272 --> 00:18:15,413
Calenmi made a choice early on, if you want to make an XCOM clone,

274
00:18:15,933 --> 00:18:18,875
to put the data on the edges rather than on the grid points.

275
00:18:19,375 --> 00:18:19,995
Do not do that.

276
00:18:21,716 --> 00:18:24,137
That's come back to haunt us quite a bit.

277
00:18:24,717 --> 00:18:25,677
It complicates things.

278
00:18:26,257 --> 00:18:28,118
When you can come, like you can have a...

279
00:18:28,758 --> 00:18:30,559
So when you have corners, for instance, right?

280
00:18:31,839 --> 00:18:33,620
That's a complicated setup all of a sudden,

281
00:18:33,660 --> 00:18:35,501
where if you just had a specific...

282
00:18:35,913 --> 00:18:42,120
Corner tile like metadata that said it was a corner you could treat it as such right away now. We were a little bit too

283
00:18:43,081 --> 00:18:46,325
Free with what we could do so you can then you can make you know t-junction

284
00:18:46,365 --> 00:18:51,131
Setups and all that because we were putting everything on our edges, so I wouldn't do that again

285
00:18:53,427 --> 00:18:59,572
Callie, I want to give you some time to have some fun here.

286
00:19:00,333 --> 00:19:05,437
Callie, I'm curious, this is a small team, this is a small company, and I think something

287
00:19:05,477 --> 00:19:08,980
that I didn't understand until I started talking to game developers was that...

288
00:19:10,901 --> 00:19:22,265
Everything you look at in a game takes time to make and what we're looking at, you know, just this one house and layout area we're looking at right now is way more time than I could have ever imagined, I'd say three or four years ago.

289
00:19:23,345 --> 00:19:34,009
What do you think helps you and your colleagues out being able to make assets for a handcrafted level, like handcrafted levels as opposed to procedural levels?

290
00:19:35,029 --> 00:19:38,971
How are you able to do it efficiently and make things so that a small team could manage it?

291
00:19:42,076 --> 00:19:52,181
It's probably a combination of Unreal being pretty flexible and also, I mean we have been

292
00:19:52,281 --> 00:19:54,302
using outsourcing quite a lot.

293
00:19:55,823 --> 00:20:01,086
One of our first recruits was actually an outsourcing manager and artist.

294
00:20:01,946 --> 00:20:05,608
So yeah.

295
00:20:08,679 --> 00:20:13,880
I believe that was key to get some help as a small studio, so we knew we could get that

296
00:20:13,900 --> 00:20:14,060
help.

297
00:20:14,100 --> 00:20:18,841
But then in the end, when it comes to the characters and stuff, I mean, a little bit

298
00:20:18,861 --> 00:20:20,562
has been outsourced, but mostly done in-house.

299
00:20:21,002 --> 00:20:26,103
When it comes to the levels, it has been done in-house.

300
00:20:26,883 --> 00:20:32,285
Basically everything, only props, has been outsourced, I guess.

301
00:20:34,424 --> 00:20:38,366
I think one thing technically as well that helped a little bit is that we didn't go in

302
00:20:38,426 --> 00:20:41,067
any baked lighting for the games.

303
00:20:41,087 --> 00:20:45,770
It was mostly outdoors, it wouldn't really bring up the fidelity maybe that much anyway,

304
00:20:46,090 --> 00:20:51,032
but it was a choice early on mostly actually from a production standpoint because, you

305
00:20:51,052 --> 00:20:55,734
know, relighting levels whenever we do something would have been too much for us.

306
00:21:00,565 --> 00:21:02,447
It's a case of making smart decisions as well.

307
00:21:02,487 --> 00:21:05,870
It's like looking at your team and who you have on the team and what they're strong in.

308
00:21:07,191 --> 00:21:11,714
For the main story beats, we use these 2D cutscenes.

309
00:21:12,855 --> 00:21:17,799
It's because we have a member of the team who is an amazing 2D artist.

310
00:21:18,219 --> 00:21:20,261
He's actually a traditional painter.

311
00:21:21,822 --> 00:21:26,165
So it's like, OK, well, we have someone who is crazy good at 2D art, so we should use that.

312
00:21:28,342 --> 00:21:30,264
Yeah, exactly. Leverage what you've got.

313
00:21:30,304 --> 00:21:34,887
Yeah, leverage your streams.

314
00:21:34,967 --> 00:21:38,690
Which artist is that, by the way? We should credit them for the great art we're looking at right now.

315
00:21:40,351 --> 00:21:42,953
Oscar. Oscar Bodine.

316
00:21:43,233 --> 00:21:43,634
Yeah.

317
00:21:44,014 --> 00:21:46,776
Nice. Oscar did a good job on these, I think.

318
00:21:49,579 --> 00:21:50,840
What made you all make...

319
00:21:51,280 --> 00:21:55,844
I played another stealth tactical game earlier this year called Phantom Doctrine.

320
00:21:55,864 --> 00:21:58,306
It was really good. I liked it a lot.

321
00:21:59,207 --> 00:22:05,152
But it could be kind of a slower game because even though it was a stealth game that also had XCOM combat...

322
00:22:07,613 --> 00:22:12,193
They did a turn-based stealth thing, which was fun, but also, like I said, it took a while.

323
00:22:14,234 --> 00:22:17,794
It seems like you guys have more experience with making stealth games than making XCOM games,

324
00:22:18,735 --> 00:22:22,275
but what was your sort of guiding philosophy for doing stealth in this kind of setting?

325
00:22:22,895 --> 00:22:26,276
And knowing that players would probably want to barge into combat anyway,

326
00:22:27,876 --> 00:22:33,317
given the, you know, it's an XCOM game, you move units and you shoot things.

327
00:22:35,576 --> 00:22:45,459
Yeah, quite early on from almost day one we made the decision that we wanted to keep the stealth aspect as simple as we possibly could.

328
00:22:46,779 --> 00:22:55,962
A reason for that was we didn't want the players spending any more time there than we needed to kind of tell the story and let you explore the world.

329
00:22:56,062 --> 00:23:04,464
Because what we wanted you to do was to do the stealth moments or you know set up for combat while you're in real time so we could speed it up a little bit.

330
00:23:05,182 --> 00:23:07,783
But if we started adding too much functionality to that,

331
00:23:08,143 --> 00:23:09,663
it would slow it down again, right?

332
00:23:09,743 --> 00:23:11,484
So we made a decision very early on

333
00:23:11,504 --> 00:23:14,585
that we wanted to keep the amount of game mechanics

334
00:23:14,625 --> 00:23:16,825
that you can utilize in the real time to a minimum

335
00:23:17,325 --> 00:23:18,746
and keep it very, very simple.

336
00:23:18,866 --> 00:23:22,967
So that's shown, for instance, in the attention circles

337
00:23:23,007 --> 00:23:24,887
that we use rather than any vision cones

338
00:23:24,927 --> 00:23:25,607
or anything like that.

339
00:23:25,627 --> 00:23:28,448
We didn't want people trying to sneak on a corner too much

340
00:23:28,568 --> 00:23:29,908
and spend too much time doing that.

341
00:23:30,909 --> 00:23:34,631
Yeah, because I assume the vision circles make it easier to let the player know,

342
00:23:34,671 --> 00:23:37,372
hey, this is where they notice you and this is where they don't,

343
00:23:37,412 --> 00:23:41,234
as opposed to like nitty-gritty Hitman style trying to, you know,

344
00:23:41,815 --> 00:23:44,996
keep at the corner of an NPC's vision or something.

345
00:23:45,957 --> 00:23:47,457
Yeah, exactly. That was the choice.

346
00:23:47,517 --> 00:23:49,879
It was either that or, you know, giving them...

347
00:23:50,179 --> 00:23:52,920
Whenever you get discovered, you get a little bit of leeway time.

348
00:23:53,642 --> 00:23:55,723
As we would have done in Hitman, for instance.

349
00:23:56,043 --> 00:23:58,765
You know, the guy would come over and investigate,

350
00:23:58,845 --> 00:24:00,246
but that gave us other problems, right?

351
00:24:00,706 --> 00:24:02,087
For balancing the game.

352
00:24:02,827 --> 00:24:04,748
So that was quite early a decision.

353
00:24:05,489 --> 00:24:05,909
Yeah.

354
00:24:06,229 --> 00:24:12,073
That we don't put anything extra that we didn't need into the real time.

355
00:24:12,153 --> 00:24:14,374
And as you can see, the attention circles here now are like,

356
00:24:14,514 --> 00:24:17,556
as long as you stay out of them, you have the advantage, right?

357
00:24:17,977 --> 00:24:18,297
Yeah.

358
00:24:18,377 --> 00:24:20,098
And that communicates very, very clearly.

359
00:24:20,606 --> 00:24:25,268
I really like the little red highlights that come up as you get close to them.

360
00:24:25,388 --> 00:24:29,970
It's almost like a stove that's too warm.

361
00:24:29,990 --> 00:24:38,794
Yeah, I think the idea was that this should be a tense moment, but you shouldn't feel stressed about it, so to speak.

362
00:24:38,934 --> 00:24:45,857
You should feel that you have the time to check out the guy coming in on a patrol here and see what's behind him, etc.

363
00:24:46,737 --> 00:24:47,818
Before setting up and then...

364
00:24:48,990 --> 00:24:53,154
If it were vision cone based for instance, that vision cone might just BAM come all of

365
00:24:53,194 --> 00:24:57,938
a sudden as he steps in behind, from behind a building or a car or something, right?

366
00:24:57,958 --> 00:25:02,943
We didn't want to make it too skill based basically.

367
00:25:03,684 --> 00:25:08,268
When you sneak around it should be more about making a tactical decision rather than being

368
00:25:08,308 --> 00:25:11,010
stressed and making quick decisions.

369
00:25:11,791 --> 00:25:14,874
For instance, you should have climbed the roof of the petrol station here.

370
00:25:15,975 --> 00:25:16,815
Oh, well, you know.

371
00:25:44,039 --> 00:25:45,860
Yeah, that's what's happening.

372
00:25:45,880 --> 00:25:48,761
If we're watching the footage right now, that's actually what's happening.

373
00:25:48,781 --> 00:25:56,165
Like, I was surprised to discover this, that you could just sort of sneak your characters around and pick off the isolated enemies.

374
00:25:56,425 --> 00:25:57,405
That's really nifty.

375
00:25:57,425 --> 00:26:01,467
Like, that's something XCOM doesn't have, because once combat starts in XCOM, combat starts.

376
00:26:01,487 --> 00:26:06,310
Like, there's no more, you know, sneaking around a level.

377
00:26:07,950 --> 00:26:14,673
Is there anything in particular you had to set up to make sure that players could figure out that they could do this kind of thing?

378
00:26:14,693 --> 00:26:18,354
So that they didn't just barge into combat every time?

379
00:26:18,374 --> 00:26:29,718
I mean, the very start of the game that you're just seeing now is very much designed to be a general introduction to stuff.

380
00:26:29,758 --> 00:26:35,740
So some extremely obvious patrols of guys with low health walking around on their own.

381
00:26:36,875 --> 00:26:41,777
It's not very taxing, it's not very challenging, and the characters when they talk, they're

382
00:26:41,797 --> 00:26:46,779
heavily hinting at least two or three times that we should investigate who's here and

383
00:26:46,799 --> 00:26:49,520
we should sneak around first.

384
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:55,342
So I would say the first 20 minutes of the game is gently kind of pushing the player

385
00:26:56,142 --> 00:27:00,544
into this kind of play style rather than us hitting them with a hammer.

386
00:27:01,084 --> 00:27:02,505
If that makes sense.

387
00:27:03,685 --> 00:27:05,646
When was it useful to hit players with a hammer though?

388
00:27:08,141 --> 00:27:10,003
Well that would be the tutorial screen I guess.

389
00:27:10,323 --> 00:27:15,086
Actually it is a good one because we had in user research about a month ago or something

390
00:27:15,106 --> 00:27:20,450
it was one of the things that we probably didn't communicate enough.

391
00:27:20,590 --> 00:27:25,794
We have added some tutorial messages around this because if you don't figure it out rather

392
00:27:25,854 --> 00:27:31,278
quickly the levels can become quite hard later down the line because we really wanted you

393
00:27:31,378 --> 00:27:32,979
to scout out these positions.

394
00:27:32,999 --> 00:27:34,360
You don't always have to pick up.

395
00:27:34,958 --> 00:27:37,639
everybody around the map, but at least figure out that they're there.

396
00:27:37,659 --> 00:27:43,580
Or when more advanced units step into the field that can help other units and such,

397
00:27:43,620 --> 00:27:47,621
it's very important that you know about these units or they will surprise you.

398
00:27:49,342 --> 00:27:53,903
Yeah, it was also important that the stealth doesn't become boring in the game.

399
00:27:54,063 --> 00:27:55,643
Because this pattern that we are doing now,

400
00:27:56,663 --> 00:27:59,024
you repeat that too much, it will start becoming stale.

401
00:28:00,835 --> 00:28:05,357
when the game is balancing, the enemies that get harder, the further into the zone you'll get

402
00:28:05,937 --> 00:28:10,139
and the enemy's health will slowly start to track ahead of your stealth weapons

403
00:28:11,179 --> 00:28:16,901
so at some point in the game you're going to start having to use multiple characters with stealth weapons to kill an enemy

404
00:28:17,461 --> 00:28:22,863
or make use of your mutations that allow you to do double damage or crit damage and stuff like that

405
00:28:23,483 --> 00:28:24,583
to be able to pull off a stealth kill

406
00:28:28,779 --> 00:28:33,463
Now you're out of combat, but of course we have a critical hit and a regular one, and that's the balance you were talking about.

407
00:28:33,623 --> 00:28:35,964
It comes kind of in layers, that balance, it's quite nice.

408
00:28:36,425 --> 00:28:47,032
Where, yeah, during the mid-game you have to start doing critical hits with your silent weapons in order to take these straggling characters out, or these outliers, right?

409
00:28:47,452 --> 00:28:49,994
So it becomes a little bit deeper to do it, which is quite nice.

410
00:28:50,034 --> 00:28:57,420
And then towards the end, yeah, you'll have to use basically all the tricks in the book if you want to take anybody out on the outskirts.

411
00:28:58,054 --> 00:29:20,681
Right on. That's actually kind of, that's interesting in that I've been playing a lot of Assassin's Creed Odyssey and just thinking about, I've been thinking about how like familiar routine I fell into with that game as far as, I can sort of feel where the game wants me to improvise and you know just sort of roll with it if things escalate and go badly, but if you're very careful you can make a very, you know, repetitive

412
00:29:21,622 --> 00:29:27,548
I'm going to move on to another question, which is, XCOM is sort of infamous in some ways for how it communicates hit percentages.

413
00:29:38,761 --> 00:29:43,643
It's kind of, I think it's considered a positive element in some respects because players don't

414
00:29:43,683 --> 00:29:46,824
seem to be averse to the idea of missing a 90% shot.

415
00:29:47,204 --> 00:29:50,325
You know, at close range, like you stand there and fire the big gun and the alien doesn't

416
00:29:50,365 --> 00:29:50,745
get hit.

417
00:29:51,505 --> 00:29:53,446
I noticed that hit percentages were a thing in this game.

418
00:29:53,806 --> 00:29:56,707
What did you learn about communicating those values to players?

419
00:29:56,987 --> 00:30:01,708
And I know there's some lies, like XCOM is lying to you sometimes about percentages and

420
00:30:01,728 --> 00:30:04,129
a lot of tactical games will actually do that to you.

421
00:30:04,929 --> 00:30:07,570
What did you learn about that from your own perspective?

422
00:30:08,210 --> 00:30:09,551
How did that affect your design decisions?

423
00:30:11,291 --> 00:30:14,853
Well, first of all, of course, we're also cheating behind the scenes

424
00:30:14,933 --> 00:30:20,475
because people do not understand percentages very well.

425
00:30:20,515 --> 00:30:23,536
So a 75% shot here is a bit higher, right?

426
00:30:23,736 --> 00:30:23,976
Yeah.

427
00:30:24,076 --> 00:30:27,737
And we'll also do a few tricks on the AI side

428
00:30:27,797 --> 00:30:31,679
where if they hit you, they'll actually have less chance next time and such

429
00:30:31,959 --> 00:30:33,900
so that you don't get into these streaks of the...

430
00:30:34,353 --> 00:30:37,295
The enemy feeling super powerful just because they got a lucky run.

431
00:30:38,735 --> 00:30:44,837
You need to do a couple of these things, specifically around 50%, right?

432
00:30:45,338 --> 00:30:48,199
I think 25-50% is where people...

433
00:30:48,919 --> 00:30:50,620
You shouldn't be taking those shots, really.

434
00:30:51,140 --> 00:30:53,761
You shouldn't be taking 25% shots in an XCOM game.

435
00:30:54,261 --> 00:30:57,042
People expect 4-25% shots to be a hit.

436
00:30:58,242 --> 00:31:02,304
So one way of doing that then, of course, is to add a bit when you miss, for instance.

437
00:31:03,770 --> 00:31:06,230
So we have a few of those tricks going on behind the scenes.

438
00:31:08,051 --> 00:31:11,812
And I think it doesn't deter anything from the game.

439
00:31:12,832 --> 00:31:15,652
We added more along the line where we felt it was needed.

440
00:31:16,513 --> 00:31:20,674
It's better that the game feels fair than that it is fair.

441
00:31:20,914 --> 00:31:21,114
Right.

442
00:31:21,614 --> 00:31:24,094
That's actually the hardest thing to do in these games is to make them feel fair.

443
00:31:24,894 --> 00:31:27,755
Yeah, and Lee was also very early on with the percentages.

444
00:31:30,299 --> 00:31:33,501
He wanted it to be... we looked at Mario Rabbids vs Rabbids, I think?

445
00:31:33,741 --> 00:31:34,982
Yeah, I think they do 150.

446
00:31:35,043 --> 00:31:36,444
Yeah, they're...

447
00:31:36,584 --> 00:31:38,605
They're more extreme than we are.

448
00:31:38,706 --> 00:31:40,687
Yeah, but you...

449
00:31:41,488 --> 00:31:42,929
We went with the system in between.

