00:31:43,269 --> 00:31:47,393
Yeah, we went for like an in-between system, where we round the numbers up to the nearest 25%.

451
00:31:48,494 --> 00:31:48,914
I think it is.

452
00:31:49,434 --> 00:31:49,615
Yeah.

453
00:31:50,575 --> 00:31:52,297
Because it just feels...

454
00:31:53,938 --> 00:31:54,679
a bit more...

455
00:31:54,999 --> 00:31:58,582
For me personally, when I'm playing, it just feels a bit more easier to predict what's going to happen.

456
00:31:59,965 --> 00:32:08,051
a 75% is not, to me it feels not guaranteed, it's still a bit of a gamble.

457
00:32:08,111 --> 00:32:10,793
50% feels like, we know what a 50-50 is, it's a complete gamble.

458
00:32:11,553 --> 00:32:14,696
If you're going to hit 25, that just feels like it's going to miss.

459
00:32:16,357 --> 00:32:24,162
Whereas if I'm playing and I'm getting an 87% chance to hit, that's a little bit more difficult for me to get a feel for what that number means to me.

460
00:32:25,503 --> 00:32:26,263
I'm taking my shot.

461
00:32:26,721 --> 00:32:30,443
How do you, um, uh, so it's kind of interesting that there's almost like there's two calculations

462
00:32:30,483 --> 00:32:31,043
going on there.

463
00:32:31,063 --> 00:32:35,165
There's the first calculation that I assume just checks, you know, it checks enemy level,

464
00:32:35,225 --> 00:32:37,906
it checks your player's level, it checks the player's gear.

465
00:32:38,706 --> 00:32:40,867
Then there's a rounded number that's presented to the player.

466
00:32:41,127 --> 00:32:49,011
Um, uh, what, uh, what internally, uh, are you, do you think makes for like, like from

467
00:32:49,091 --> 00:32:49,111
a...

468
00:32:49,931 --> 00:32:57,817
I guess thinking about making those formulas, what do you think makes a good version of those formulas from the dev side before it's presented to the player?

469
00:33:00,099 --> 00:33:13,568
Oh, that's a good question. But I think rounding was a little bit wrong, because what we did is basically we said that all your bonuses are on like a 25%, so a low cover will give you 25%, while a high cover will give you 50, right?

470
00:33:13,588 --> 00:33:13,668
Yeah.

471
00:33:13,688 --> 00:33:13,809
Yeah.

472
00:33:19,259 --> 00:33:20,940
instead of going with 10% cent.

473
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:22,241
or, you know, some certain angle.

474
00:33:22,541 --> 00:33:26,423
Trying to be a little bit more binary so that players will learn that,

475
00:33:26,523 --> 00:33:28,364
okay, I'm gonna take 75% shots.

476
00:33:28,484 --> 00:33:31,225
Or try to get 100 because in our game, it's quite easy to get 100.

477
00:33:31,866 --> 00:33:34,407
As long as you flank an enemy, you will most likely be getting it.

478
00:33:34,447 --> 00:33:35,848
We do have range in there.

479
00:33:37,188 --> 00:33:39,369
But that's what we wanted.

480
00:33:39,409 --> 00:33:42,931
We wanted players to figure out how to get 75 or 100 shots every time right.

481
00:33:42,951 --> 00:33:43,131
MmmmHmm.

482
00:33:46,610 --> 00:33:53,478
I'm not sure if this is a good idea, but I'm going to try to be pretty harsh on the other end.

483
00:33:54,238 --> 00:33:57,762
I'd rather give you 0% than 5% because we don't want you taking 5% shots anyway.

484
00:33:58,523 --> 00:34:01,045
It was right to try and make the game feel a lot more fair.

485
00:34:01,286 --> 00:34:07,832
We want to reward players for doing good tactical moves a lot more than other tactical games will do.

486
00:34:11,310 --> 00:34:18,233
If I'm flanking someone and I only get a 82% chance to hit and I miss, it doesn't feel

487
00:34:18,253 --> 00:34:21,835
like I'm being rewarded for doing some good tactical play.

488
00:34:22,156 --> 00:34:28,499
So in our game if you do a good tactical play and good positioning, which the stealth is

489
00:34:29,059 --> 00:34:32,781
directly feeding into, then you'll be rewarded pretty highly.

490
00:34:38,359 --> 00:34:43,843
solved completely here, which is teaching players what flanking means.

491
00:34:44,304 --> 00:34:48,327
Because it's the same rules as XCOM uses, which basically means you need to be on the same,

492
00:34:49,208 --> 00:34:56,254
like, behind the grid point that the cover is on. But since we have quite lush environments

493
00:34:56,294 --> 00:35:00,397
that look almost biological at times, it can be really hard to communicate that.

494
00:35:03,638 --> 00:35:07,421
We opted to go for the, let's see if you switch to combat here,

495
00:35:07,781 --> 00:35:13,766
making sure that we show the line of fire and kind of your percentages to all the characters

496
00:35:15,447 --> 00:35:19,109
in a preview from any tile that you want to move to.

497
00:35:19,249 --> 00:35:24,613
And then that way you could kind of explore where you would get the best advantage.

498
00:35:25,174 --> 00:35:30,177
I'm not sure what's in this demo actually, because we've been adding a little bit to that lately.

499
00:35:31,498 --> 00:35:32,899
Well, let's see when you get into combat.

500
00:35:33,645 --> 00:35:36,507
This gets really interesting because I totally thought I was boned here.

501
00:35:36,587 --> 00:35:37,087
But uh...

502
00:35:38,107 --> 00:35:41,429
Now you have this guy behind the house.

503
00:35:42,629 --> 00:35:44,090
And he's a silent weapon, yeah.

504
00:35:44,270 --> 00:35:46,471
Yeah, but that was a tense moment, right?

505
00:35:46,771 --> 00:35:47,071
Yeah.

506
00:35:47,091 --> 00:35:48,632
I've been caught there as well.

507
00:35:49,832 --> 00:35:53,714
I liked how he came to look for me and I was just kind of panicked into a corner.

508
00:35:54,434 --> 00:35:55,955
And I was like, ah, what do I do?

509
00:35:56,035 --> 00:35:57,035
Fire, fire, fire!

510
00:35:57,155 --> 00:35:59,737
And it worked out okay.

511
00:36:00,932 --> 00:36:06,419
Yeah, you should be careful there because the boar doesn't have a silent weapon at the moment, right?

512
00:36:06,780 --> 00:36:12,547
Yeah, yeah, yeah. You can see I stuck him here to get ready to fight while I move my duck around.

513
00:36:12,567 --> 00:36:13,148
Yep.

514
00:36:15,150 --> 00:36:17,873
I guess that brings us back to the environment a little bit, which is...

515
00:36:20,746 --> 00:36:35,417
What do you think helped you move from the vision of exploring the woods and finding random buildings in the woods to taking those woods and making them locales that could make for these interesting decisions?

516
00:36:37,278 --> 00:36:38,579
It's sort of easy, I think, to...

517
00:36:38,719 --> 00:36:40,699
Well, no, nothing in game development is easy.

518
00:36:40,739 --> 00:36:41,279
What am I saying?

519
00:36:42,340 --> 00:36:48,202
It is one thing to make a lush rendered scene that's interesting to explore,

520
00:36:48,602 --> 00:36:51,763
and then it's another to say, like, that one bit of cover out there...

521
00:36:52,103 --> 00:36:53,343
You can't see me pointing. What am I doing?

522
00:36:53,383 --> 00:36:55,564
That one box on the right side of the screen right now

523
00:36:56,004 --> 00:37:00,685
is its own strategically-paced bit of cover that changes the flow of gameplay here.

524
00:37:00,725 --> 00:37:03,386
Like, what's that process like moving from, like, the...

525
00:37:04,784 --> 00:37:07,126
This is a high level to low level here.

526
00:37:08,767 --> 00:37:10,248
Yeah, it's difficult to explain.

527
00:37:12,990 --> 00:37:15,252
Just a lot of play testing.

528
00:37:15,612 --> 00:37:16,673
That's the only way you can do it.

529
00:37:16,693 --> 00:37:18,194
I mean, this map that you're seeing right now,

530
00:37:18,234 --> 00:37:20,555
I must have played this a thousand times.

531
00:37:21,476 --> 00:37:23,718
And every time I play, I adjust the covers around,

532
00:37:23,798 --> 00:37:24,618
and then I play again.

533
00:37:24,638 --> 00:37:25,559
And then I'm like,

534
00:37:25,739 --> 00:37:27,620
ah, this would have been so much better if I had a cover here.

535
00:37:28,161 --> 00:37:29,202
Then I adjust the covers around,

536
00:37:29,342 --> 00:37:31,843
and just keep doing that process over and over again.

537
00:37:31,863 --> 00:37:33,565
Yeah, because it's...

538
00:37:35,457 --> 00:37:40,940
I remember when we generated trees, for instance, at some point, we had a distance that we wanted

539
00:37:40,960 --> 00:37:42,701
to put them so that you could always get a cover.

540
00:37:42,741 --> 00:37:46,584
But that doesn't work to make an interesting space in itself.

541
00:37:47,124 --> 00:37:50,526
So I think, yeah, there's no shortcut there.

542
00:37:50,666 --> 00:37:51,987
You really have to play it.

543
00:37:53,288 --> 00:37:56,170
I mean, there are some ground rules, I guess you learned after a while that, you know,

544
00:37:56,850 --> 00:38:02,054
you need to have four tiles between high cover walls in buildings or such.

545
00:38:03,849 --> 00:38:06,330
Sometimes it's fun to remove covers from an area as well.

546
00:38:06,670 --> 00:38:08,371
So the player has to make completely different decisions.

547
00:38:08,411 --> 00:38:11,952
Maybe they have to make a sprint move to get to the good covers at the other side.

548
00:38:13,313 --> 00:38:16,535
But the only real way of doing this is through just a lot of play testing.

549
00:38:23,452 --> 00:38:28,074
Yeah, I got lucky with that. I mean, I had this under control. There's only one of them.

550
00:38:28,514 --> 00:38:28,734
Yeah.

551
00:38:29,494 --> 00:38:34,316
Steakapplebeats would like to know, what were your main takeaways from the beta period for this game?

552
00:38:38,157 --> 00:38:42,599
That it is a large game to balance?

553
00:38:43,299 --> 00:38:43,539
Yes.

554
00:38:43,679 --> 00:38:46,160
It's the hardest thing I've ever done.

555
00:38:49,341 --> 00:38:50,982
I mean, it is...

556
00:38:52,416 --> 00:38:58,318
It's about 15 hours of gameplay, even for us that know the game very well, to try and get through it.

557
00:38:58,858 --> 00:39:05,800
And of course, like we discussed earlier, we changed the balance for the stealth, for one.

558
00:39:06,240 --> 00:39:07,981
So like, how many units you can take out.

559
00:39:09,762 --> 00:39:13,303
Then you can take them out if you use the correct strategies, right?

560
00:39:14,599 --> 00:39:22,084
Lots and lots of balancing and really really tricky to balance the whole way because of the amount of time, right?

561
00:39:23,324 --> 00:39:27,727
Yeah, and I think one of the big things that have hit us from the the public

562
00:39:28,448 --> 00:39:29,648
demo that went out was

563
00:39:30,449 --> 00:39:31,049
the response

564
00:39:32,110 --> 00:39:35,072
It's taken me by surprise how much people are enjoying the game

565
00:39:35,752 --> 00:39:41,836
Because we're we're completely closed. We're completely close to the game. So we can't see it anymore. We're completely blind to it and

566
00:39:42,308 --> 00:39:44,890
There's the old saying with game developers, we only deal with problems.

567
00:39:46,031 --> 00:39:47,913
That's how our entire day is, just problems all day long.

568
00:39:49,314 --> 00:39:53,217
We never take a step back and go, oh, wait a minute, maybe we're actually building something that people really like.

569
00:39:53,817 --> 00:40:01,684
Yeah, but it was for balancing because we have two completely different answers from two different people, right?

570
00:40:05,535 --> 00:40:11,217
Rui, the CEO of Funcom, he's a really hardcore XCOM fan and he's constantly been telling

571
00:40:11,257 --> 00:40:12,937
us to make it harder and harder and harder.

572
00:40:15,298 --> 00:40:19,879
We have people that are not hardcore XCOM players, right, and they're all like, it's

573
00:40:19,899 --> 00:40:21,159
way too hard, it's way too hard.

574
00:40:22,119 --> 00:40:27,881
And then you have, because we went with this option that you can take people out silently,

575
00:40:28,061 --> 00:40:31,722
that became another one, not just balancing a fight.

576
00:40:32,785 --> 00:40:35,426
But if you don't take anybody out, that fight will be very hard.

577
00:40:35,587 --> 00:40:38,168
If you take as many as possible out, it might become too easy.

578
00:40:38,908 --> 00:40:41,309
So that's been a tricky one.

579
00:40:41,969 --> 00:40:42,589
Have you had to...

580
00:40:42,970 --> 00:40:45,571
I'm sorry, go for it, Lee.

581
00:40:46,231 --> 00:40:48,112
A top tip for any game designers out there,

582
00:40:48,192 --> 00:40:50,373
stick all your numbers in a big Excel sheet

583
00:40:51,153 --> 00:40:52,434
and make some formulas in there.

584
00:40:53,154 --> 00:40:54,615
So if you change one number somewhere,

585
00:40:54,675 --> 00:40:56,115
you can see what it does to the rest of the game.

586
00:40:56,735 --> 00:40:57,276
Yeah.

587
00:40:57,616 --> 00:40:58,616
That's my approach with this.

588
00:40:58,736 --> 00:41:01,938
And it's the only way I've been able to get on top of it, I would say.

589
00:41:02,893 --> 00:41:09,157
If I change how much damage the crossbow does over here, I can roughly see where it is at the end game.

590
00:41:11,218 --> 00:41:13,740
We've finally become old enough to praise Excel.

591
00:41:13,880 --> 00:41:14,060
Yeah.

592
00:41:15,461 --> 00:41:15,781
I know.

593
00:41:15,801 --> 00:41:22,545
We were making fun of Skype earlier, but I think the number one thing is Excel.

594
00:41:22,585 --> 00:41:26,207
I think that's the one thing I've learned from game designers is Excel is wonderful.

595
00:41:26,547 --> 00:41:27,868
Skype is nightmarish.

596
00:41:29,755 --> 00:41:38,820
Yeah, it's true. I think that was probably the biggest thing we went through during the beta period now was just how large the game was.

597
00:41:40,941 --> 00:41:46,423
It's always hard to say how many gameplay hours you have as well, of course, early on.

598
00:41:46,804 --> 00:41:52,627
And we were playing this in different segments, you know, calling it like you would, the start of the game, the mid-game, and then like the end game.

599
00:41:52,687 --> 00:41:56,288
And we were just playing those segments, but never doing that full run.

600
00:41:58,145 --> 00:42:00,708
You want to do it as early as possible, we always do it too late.

601
00:42:01,808 --> 00:42:06,633
And in our case, that meant we had a lot of hours to balance all of a sudden.

602
00:42:06,673 --> 00:42:11,517
So maybe, um, maybe we should have, uh, I don't know what we should have changed,

603
00:42:11,557 --> 00:42:11,977
to be honest.

604
00:42:12,057 --> 00:42:12,938
It's just a large game.

605
00:42:15,300 --> 00:42:19,183
Um, Lee, I wanted to follow up on the, the kind of one that you halfway talked

606
00:42:19,203 --> 00:42:22,406
about it with, uh, an Excel spreadsheet with formulas that can change.

607
00:42:23,700 --> 00:42:29,004
Did you find yourself making new formulas as development went on?

608
00:42:29,084 --> 00:42:36,328
I assume you had some sort of core balancing formulas and then made things that were tuned for specific gameplay instances.

609
00:42:36,428 --> 00:42:40,170
But after that beta period, we were sort of like, okay, I need to solve this tiny problem.

610
00:42:40,210 --> 00:42:45,233
That means I need to create this kind of formula to create something more that doesn't...

611
00:42:45,574 --> 00:42:50,136
It lets me not have to change all the base values and lets you be more flexible.

612
00:42:52,485 --> 00:43:00,309
Not as such. The Excel sheet I've been using for most of production has not changed much,

613
00:43:00,329 --> 00:43:07,052
it always changes the numbers that's in it. And the hardest thing to balance is the stealth.

614
00:43:08,273 --> 00:43:12,815
Making sure it's not too powerful, but also making sure it's not weak at the same time.

615
00:43:13,476 --> 00:43:15,817
And also making sure it doesn't get boring halfway into the game.

616
00:43:20,026 --> 00:43:21,627
Right on. Grabbing a question from chat.

617
00:43:22,028 --> 00:43:23,669
Magervalp would like to know,

618
00:43:25,090 --> 00:43:27,692
do scrap and enemies respawn so that players can grind?

619
00:43:27,792 --> 00:43:31,355
I noticed while I'm in the zone, nothing respawns,

620
00:43:31,415 --> 00:43:33,317
but I didn't return to any zones during the demo.

621
00:43:33,937 --> 00:43:37,440
And I guess the follow-up question I would ask is,

622
00:43:37,600 --> 00:43:41,303
why or why not did you implement grinding in this game

623
00:43:41,323 --> 00:43:44,305
so that players could just sort of keep gathering stuff?

624
00:43:47,088 --> 00:43:47,408
We didn't.

625
00:43:49,795 --> 00:43:57,381
Early on we actually had many meta loops that we tried out and grinding in such a

626
00:43:57,441 --> 00:44:01,985
slow-paced game as a XCOM turn-based we felt was probably not the right way to

627
00:44:02,025 --> 00:44:07,309
go. So that also I mean that makes it harder to balance in a way as well

628
00:44:07,530 --> 00:44:10,312
because if you have the grinding element of course that becomes a little bit of a

629
00:44:11,313 --> 00:44:14,976
self-balancing act from the player how much they want to you know level up

630
00:44:14,996 --> 00:44:15,796
before doing something.

631
00:44:18,185 --> 00:44:20,326
But we cut that quite early.

632
00:44:20,686 --> 00:44:24,267
It was quite early, but we did some tests with it and it wasn't really working.

633
00:44:25,068 --> 00:44:29,570
No, we felt it was not the route to go and instead tried to...

634
00:44:29,870 --> 00:44:34,372
What we have though instead is we have optional maps.

635
00:44:35,433 --> 00:44:39,694
So there are forks in the road when you move around the map here.

636
00:44:40,775 --> 00:44:46,798
And there are certain almost hidden areas that you don't need to do for the story or you don't need to do to progress.

637
00:44:48,048 --> 00:44:53,952
But you can come back to it, so if you skipped them and went further in the game and it starts becoming too hard,

638
00:44:54,132 --> 00:44:56,134
then of course you could return to them at that point.

639
00:44:57,374 --> 00:45:03,719
So that's kind of our grind, those extra non-story.

640
00:45:04,620 --> 00:45:11,165
Yeah, and we found as well that without having the grind in there, it allowed us to get the balance in very, very tight.

641
00:45:12,225 --> 00:45:16,068
So we can balance it so you only just have enough medpacks, you only just have enough scrap.

642
00:45:17,436 --> 00:45:22,720
Because in a game like this, your resources really matter in the tactical side.

643
00:45:23,901 --> 00:45:32,227
If you can grind for unlimited medpacks, then the tactical side of the game becomes a bit meaningless.

644
00:45:32,307 --> 00:45:35,689
There's no skill-based decision making anymore.

645
00:45:36,250 --> 00:45:39,872
There's no like, ooh, I can't really use... I should save my grenade and do something else,

646
00:45:39,932 --> 00:45:42,834
because I can just have... I've only got two of them and they're really expensive.

647
00:45:44,277 --> 00:45:48,061
That kind of gameplay disappears if you can just keep grinding the maps over and over again.

648
00:46:08,635 --> 00:46:11,157
So, that's the only thing we can say.

649
00:46:11,177 --> 00:46:13,919
And, of course, if you fail a couple of more bigger battles...

650
00:46:38,341 --> 00:46:40,685
It might take you a couple of more hours to write off the bat, right?

651
00:46:40,745 --> 00:46:45,853
Because there are some quite big fights for the later parts of the game.

652
00:46:46,772 --> 00:46:51,473
I'm actually really excited about a battle we're about to check out as we close out the

653
00:46:51,493 --> 00:46:51,993
stream today.

654
00:46:55,874 --> 00:46:59,375
After picking up Selma here, there's a really interesting battle up the hill that was the

655
00:46:59,415 --> 00:47:02,896
first time that I saw you guys spawn in new enemies.

656
00:47:03,336 --> 00:47:06,897
At first I panicked because I was like, oh no, that's way more than I expected.

657
00:47:07,737 --> 00:47:11,518
And then I realized I could deal with it, and I was like, that was one of the coolest

658
00:47:11,558 --> 00:47:12,518
feelings I've had in a...

659
00:47:13,599 --> 00:47:16,961
A strategy game is always, you know, oh no, and then wait, I can handle it.

660
00:47:17,462 --> 00:47:22,105
That kind of that movement from the first emotion to the second emotion is a really good one.

661
00:47:22,165 --> 00:47:24,587
So after I recruit Selma here, we'll get to look at that.

662
00:47:24,928 --> 00:47:26,649
We are coming to the end of our hour here.

